      <section name='clive'>

         <para number='1' comment='get/hug/kill clive'>
         Clive skitters out of the way with more speed than you would have expected, given his portly frame. "Cut that out," he whines in his nasal voice. Clearly he does not relish human contact.
         </para>

         <para number='2' comment='Clive chat - hello'>
         Clive looks up from the comic book he is reading. "Greetings, and welcome to my humble emporium," he says in a slightly whiny voice. He is attempting to be friendly but it does not come at all naturally. "If you have any questions about the merchandise please do not hesitate to ask."
         </para>

         <para number='3' comment='bye'>
         Clive mumbles a farewell under his breath, and then remembers he is supposed to be polite to his customers. "Have a nice day," he says, his sincerity quite underwhelming, then he returns to his comic book.
         </para>

         <para number='4' comment='collectible/merchandise'>
         Gesturing around the shop and pointing to individual items, Clive describes the goods on sale. "Over there we have the finest collection of ornate thimbles known to man. The collection of commemorative plates on this shelf are unparalleled. We've got stamps from the days before electronic messages, and coins from all over the Galaxy.
         </para>

         <para number='5'>
         "The action figures are from old holos; aficionados will recognize the characters, of course."
         </para>

         <para number='6'>
         Then he indicates the trading cards in the center of the counter. "These, though, these are the items I am most proud of. Nobody else sells these. They are trading cards depicting famous people. They're quite magnificent." He sighs contentedly as he contemplates his lovely trading cards.
         </para>

         <para number='7' comment='thimble'>
         "Decorative thimbles have long been something people like to collect - particularly women," says Clive. "They're not really my thing but I have built up an extensive collection, and people come from all over the Galaxy to buy them. I once sold the actual thimble that was used to blow up the pirate's asteroid, Snark - it was authenticated! I made a fortune on that sale."
         </para>

         <para number='8' comment='snark'>
         Clive leans towards you and whispers, "There are rumors that the asteroid still exists, but nobody knows how to get there - or at least, nobody is telling, but I bet the Galactic Administration knows about it and isn't telling."
         </para>

         <para number='9' comment='galactic admin'>
         "I try not to come to the notice of anybody from the government," says Clive. "I just want to be left alone to sell my collectibles."
         </para>

         <para number='10' comment='castillo'>
         "The planet is really just a research station but they decided recently they wanted to branch out a bit and introduce some retail outlets to encourage visitors," explains Clive. "My shop is the first one to open. If it's a success then I am sure there will be more."
         </para>

         <para number='11' comment='shop'>
         "I used to sell my collectibles out of my bedroom, you know, by mail order," Clive explains, "but my mom got a bit peeved and suggested that if I wanted to carry on then I had to get my own premises. That's when I decided to open a shop and sell things personally, to real visitors, not just remotely."
         </para>

         <para number='12' comment='plate'>
         "Some of my commemorative plates date back to before colonization of the Solar System, let alone the rest of the Galaxy," says Clive. "I've got one that celebrates a wedding between two members of the British royal family that you have probably never heard of. It's a shame, the plate has a crack running down the middle of it which reduces its value considerably."
         </para>

         <para number='13' comment='stamp'>
         Clive starts to give you a lecture about postage stamps. "Before messages were sent electronically, the only way to communicate over long distance was to send letters written on paper," he says. "These were carried by official messengers called postmen, and you paid for the delivery by purchasing little sticky tokens called stamps that you attached to the letters."
         </para>

         <para number='14'>
         He grins at you, "Yes, I know, it does sound very unlikely, doesn't it? But it's what really happened. Of course it was very unreliable and the post system died out once electronic messaging was invented. Anyway, there were people who collected these stamps, and even though stamps aren't used any more, collectors still want them. Weird, huh?"
         </para>

         <para number='15' comment='coin'>
         "I have coins from all over the Galaxy," Clive says proudly. "Some of them are old currency from before the fall of Ming. Look at this one..." He shows you a green coin with 13 sides and the head of a familiar-looking green person on one face. "These are very rare now, but they used to be common because they could be used in all kinds of automated vending machines."
         </para>

         <para number='16' comment='action/figure'>
         Clive picks up a figure of a person in a black helmet and a long black cloak. "You recognize him, of course," he says, running his fingers lovingly up and down the action figure. When you have to admit that you don't, he looks disappointed. "It's Darth," he says. "Darth Vader. Brave and noble hero of a series of films from long, long ago. No copies of them exist any more, but from what little is known about them, they were fantastic!"
         </para>

         <para number='17' comment='card'>
         "The trading cards are my speciality," says Clive in an excited voice. "Aren't they fantastic? The pictures are all from authentic holos. Some of them are of contemporary celebrities and some famous people from history. They are divided into sets. Right now I am featuring the Emperors set."
         </para>

         <para number='18' comment='emperor'>
         "The series shows six of the most famous Emperors," Clive says. "I'm selling them one at a time, a special each month. Once a card goes off sale it won't be available again. That makes them truly collectible. This month's card is of Catty, the last emperor."
         </para>

         <para number='19' comment='comic'>
         "It's the Adventures of Sam Galaxy," says Clive, showing you the comic. "He's a private eye and he solves mysteries and has adventures all over the Galaxy. It's really exciting."
         </para>

         <para number='20' comment='sam galaxy'>
         You can read all about Sam Galaxy and his adventures at http://www.ibgames.net/fed2/samgalaxy/index.html.
         </para>

         <para number='21' comment='promethius'>
         "The trading card showing Emperor Promethius was a previous special offer," says Clive. "It's no longer available - these collectors' items are for limited release only."
         </para>

         <para number='22' comment='Nomatch'>
         Clive shrugs - clearly he doesn't know how to respond to that, not being the Galaxy's best conversationalist!
         </para>

         <para number='23' comment='frizz'>
         "The trading card showing Emperor Frizz was a previous special offer," says Clive. "It's no longer available - these collectors' items are for limited release only."
         </para>

         <para number='24' comment='zetian'>
         "The trading card showing Emperor Zetian was a previous special offer," says Clive. "It's no longer available - these collectors' items are for limited release only."
         </para>

         <para number='25' comment='ming'>
         "The trading card showing Emperor Ming was last month's special offer," says Clive. "It's no longer available - these collectors' items are for limited release only."
         </para>

         <para number='26' comment='catty'>
         "The trading card showing Emperor Catty is this month's special offer," says Clive. He points to the card, which shows string of half hidden, semi-translucent figures appear to split off from behind the figure, each believed to represent one of Catty's alternative personalities...
         </para>

